\opening{Dear Editor,}

We wish to submit our manuscript, ``\texttt{compute-ViT}: Hardware-Aware Training for Vision Transformers on Organic Optoelectronic Crossbars,'' for your consideration as a Research Article in \textit{Nature Electronics}.

\textbf{Disclosure of post-submission bug fix.} During final code audit (2026-04-23) we identified two bugs in the analog surrogate-gradient engine: (1) an LTP/LTD branch-mapping swap in the STE backward pass, and (2) an extraneous $\mathsf{nl}$ multiplier in the second-order correction. Both were fixed at commit \texttt{9cdbe77}. The pre-fix severe-NL claims ($\\sim$30\% structural ceiling, bimodal basin narrative) were contaminated and are hereby retracted. The present manuscript reports only post-fix results, audited by independent cross-review and backed by replication runs (M-series). A prior preprint circulated before 2026-04-24 is superseded.

Post-fix hardware-aware training recovers 82.03$\pm$0.94\% fresh-instance accuracy under $NL=2.0$ severe nonlinearity (CIFAR-10, Tiny-ViT), falsifying the $\\sim$30\% ceiling. Under canonical $NL=1.0$, Ensemble HAT preserves 86.37$\\pm$1.54\% across 10 fresh arrays. The framework enables zero-shot transfer to literature-calibrated organic photodiode arrays at 88.53$\\pm$0.08\%.

We believe this work is particularly suitable for \textit{Nature Electronics} because it bridges organic optoelectronic device physics with algorithm-level hardware-aware training, providing a calibrated simulation-to-deployment pipeline that is immediately useful for the emerging OPECT foundry ecosystem.

All code, device models, and evaluation protocols are available at [repository].

